# Project Architecture

This project is a TypeScript Node module that validates and solves sudoku puzzles.

Authoritative implementation layout:
- `src/index.ts`: public module API only (`solve`, `nextMove`, `validate`, `describe`) and re-exported types.
- `src/boardGeo.ts`: `Board` type (`number[][]`).
- `src/move.ts`: `Move`, `PlacementMove`, `EliminationMove`, `MoveStatus` (each move includes `message` + `reasoning`; `Algorithm` imported from solver for typing).
- `src/sudokuSolver.ts`: `SudokuSolver` class — parsing, solving, move generation, validation, difficulty; `finalizePlacement` / `finalizeElimination` build `message` + technique-specific `reasoning`.
- `src/utils.ts`: pure helpers (`boxNumber`, `cloneBoard`, `assertBoardShape`, `parseBoardString`, `duplicateValues`, …).
- `src/validate.ts`: `ValidationReason` / `ValidationResult`, `pushUniqueReason`, string invalid factories.
- `tests/sudoku.test.ts`: solver/validator internals and fixture-driven status checks.
- `tests/module.test.ts`: module-level API behavior checks.

Rules:
- Keep `src/index.ts` thin: orchestrate input parsing and result shaping only.
- Keep solver internals in `src/sudokuSolver.ts`; avoid duplicating solve logic in API wrappers.
- Keep validation internals in `src/validate.ts`; preserve stable reason type names.
- Keep board utilities in `src/utils.ts`; keep them pure and side-effect free.
- Prefer pure functions and deterministic outputs.
- Keep TypeScript strict and avoid `any`.

Critical module contracts:
- `solve(boardInput)` returns `{ isValid, board }`; never throws for valid board shape/value domains.
- `nextMove(boardInput)` returns `{ status, move, message }`; applies the returned move via `SudokuSolver.applyMove(move)` (placement → `setSquareValue`, elimination → `applyElimination`). When `move` is non-null, `message === move.message`.
- `validate(boardInput)` returns `{ isValid, message, reasons }` and includes `invalid_board_length` / `invalid_board_characters` for invalid board strings.
- `describe(boardInput)` returns `{ isValid, isComplete, message, difficulty, solutions }`.

Solver internals:
- `possiblesGrid: number[][][]` tracks candidates per cell; initialized by `calcPossibles()` in `setBoard()`.
- `setSquareValue(row, col, value)` surgically removes `value` from peer cells (same row, col, box) rather than recalculating all candidates. This preserves any prior eliminations (e.g. from pointing moves or naked subsets).
- Pointing: `Move.algorithm` is `"Pointing Pair"` or `"Pointing Triple"` according to how many cells in the box (along one row or column) still have the digit as a candidate.
- `applyElimination(move: EliminationMove)` removes specified candidates from `possiblesGrid` without placing a digit.
- `applyMove(move: Move)` branches on `move.type` to placement vs elimination.
- `solve()` loops `findBestMove` + `applyMove` until stuck or complete.
- `findBestMove()` walks `SEARCH_PHASES` (not exported):
   1. `NakedSingle`
   2. `HiddenSingle`
   3. `Pointing`
   4. `BoxLineReduction` (if all candidates for a digit in a row/column lie within one box, eliminate from rest of that box)
   5. `NakedSubset` (pairs/triples only)
   6. `HiddenSubset` (pairs/triples only)
   7. `Fish` (classic row/column `X-Wing` only)
   8. `Swordfish` (3×3 fish: 3 base rows/columns whose candidates span exactly 3 cover columns/rows)
   9. `NakedHiddenQuads` (per house: try `Naked Quad`, then `Hidden Quad`).
  10. `XYZWing` (hinge {X,Y,Z} with bi-value pincers {X,Z} and {Y,Z} seen by hinge; eliminate Z from cells seeing all three).
- `Move.algorithm` is the specific label (e.g. `"Last Digit"`, `"Full House"`, `"Naked Pair"`); naked-single path can upgrade to Full House / Last Digit.
- Reasoning examples: pointing names `box` index (1–9, `boxNumber`); box/line reduction pattern `In row R, all candidates for D lie within box B, so D cannot appear elsewhere in box B outside that row.` (column variant replaces "row" with "column"); naked subset pattern `Naked Pair 7/9 in row 5 … same row` (digits `/`-sorted, house = row | column | box); hidden subset pattern `Hidden Pair 8/9 in column 5: in that column, those digits appear only in r3c5, r5c5, …` (reserved cells `rXcY`, digits `/`-sorted); Swordfish pattern `Swordfish on 9: rows 3, 7 and 8 have 9 only in columns 1, 5 and 8, so 9 cannot appear elsewhere in those columns.` (column-based variant swaps "rows"/"columns"); XYZ-Wing pattern `XYZ-Wing: hinge rXcY (X/Y/Z) with pincers rAcB (X/Z) and rCcD (Y/Z). One of the three cells must contain Z, so Z cannot appear in any cell that sees all three.` (hinge digits `/`-sorted).
